1. Introduction

Project Overview: The Problem the Use Case and Purpose

This model was built with the intent to correlate spatial and temporal data to parking occupancy ratios in Seattle,WA. The purpose of such an approach is to find out the characteristics of the built environment that attract more drivers to specific locations, and how this demand shifts during the day. By having these multiple variables is a single model, we expect to understand up to which degree each of those features affect the parking demand.

Such predictive power is extremely useful for urban planners, since parking is a serious problem in American cities. Municipal legislation often demands from new developments off-street parking requirements (mandatory parking minimums), which consume a large share of land - making new developments and consequently cities more expensive. This also incentivizes the use of personal vehicles over more environmentally friendly options, such as transit, biking, or walking.

Off-street parking requirements are not the only problem, though: an unbalanced offer of street parking brings an array of externalities. Vehicles in low speed searching for a parking stall in a busy areas of cities, which result in increased congestion. Charging the right fee for parking is challenging, but if the pricing is well designed, the city may maximize revenue and still have some empty spots throughout the day.

In this context, our model was conceived to help planners understand how their decisions affect the parking demands in the city. For example, when the zoning code is modified in a former industrial zone being redeveloped to accommodate commercial or residential functions, how does that affect parking demand? This can also be seen as how a specific building would affect the parking needs of a specific perimeter.

This model can be built into an app that forecasts different scenarios, which can be useful for quick consultations during a meeting or to evaluate long-term effects of policy changes. Furthermore, the app can be adapted in the future to provide price optimization, or to incorporate functionalities intended to the drivers, such as parking availability.

Results summary

In brief, our final model showed that the most significant predictors for estimating the average occupancy for a street segment was largely dependent on neighborhood characteristics such as time of the day, neighborhood location and street type, among other variables. The model could similarly predict for observed and unseen values. In conclusion, it is hard to say the model is generalizable because most of the data was trained from a dataset that mostly contained observations from the downtown area of Seattle. As such, it is more appropriate that this model is more accurate to predicting average parking occupancy for areas in downtown Seattle.

2. Data

2.1 Used Data

The two main datasets used for this model analysis were the Annual Parking Study dataset and the Seattle Streets dataset.

The Annual Parking Study Data for the city of Seattle contains a sample of the parking occupancy for street segments between 2014-2018. We have joined this data to the street pricing information for each year, by using the dynamic pricing rates found in the On-Street Paid Parking Annual Report published every year. The data is organized by street segment, which enables more specific outcomes.

The Seattle street network was fundamental to geolocate the street segments. It is also intrinsically helpful, since we added significant variables from this dataset, such as what type of street (local / collector / major), whether the street is one-way or two way, which side of the street people park, and the slope of the street.

To control for the built environment at those places, we have used the building permits data, which comprises all building permits issued or in progress within the city of Seattle. We have also used the zoning code. We have joined both of these datasets to the Seattle street shapefile using ArcGIS. The shapefile we added to our R Script is named streets_join_permits_zoning.shp.

To incorporate the building permits into our model, we have handled them in two separate ways. First, we have determined for each street segment which is the most predominant type of use (the permits are classified as single family, multifamily, commercial, institutional, industrial, or vacant). While this approach gives us helpful insight regarding the composition of the parcel, it may distort situations in which a segment has, for instance, a hospital, and several houses. In this case, the prevalent use would be single family, but the hospital would create a huge demand. We have then decided to build a parking score for each segment, which is a weighted sum of all land uses within each parcel. Vacant parcels were multiplied by 3, single family by 4, multifamily by 6, industrial by 6, institutional by 8, and commercial by 10. This aggregate score was integrated as a variable called wtScore in our model.

One promising variable that we looked at was the presence of public parking lots and garages. Our initial assumption is that those are built on places with high parking demand. So, we used Mile buffers as a dummy variable to verify if the segments were in one of those areas. However, the set of buffers of all public parking lots and garages ended up being one big shape that encompassed all the downtown area, where most of our observations are located, rendering this feature useless for our model.

A problem with numberOfSpaces==0"

After cleaning, organizing and joining all the data, we began plotting some maps to understand the spatial distribution of parking occupancy ratios. Two problems became clear to us. The first was that the Annual Parking Study observed total number of parked vehicles in areas with parking spots set as 0. What this means is that the surveyors counted how many cars were parked at places with no official stalls (we understand that those unofficial spots are places without parking meters). Since we are evaluating the ratio of number of vehicles / number of parking spots, having a 0 in the denominator would break our data set. We have then decided to add 0,001 to the vector with number of vehicles, but that created huge ratios, that would render our model useless.Finally, we decided to remove those unofficial parking spots and since they are free of charge, it may be a huge deviation from the rest of the dataset.

#reorder columns so dependent variable is first
#remove Morning, Afternoon, Evening, Night <- this is all in the RateCost column
parkRateStreets_final<-subset(parkRateStreets_noNA[c(7,1:6,12:25)])
parkingStNoZero<-filter(parkRateStreets_final,numberOfSpace>=1)

Average Occupancy by Times of Day

We want to explore how average occupancy vary by different time periods of the day. To do this, we break down the data into four different periods of the day - Morning, Afternoon, Evening, Night.

# without places where parking is not permited
baseformaps2 <- filter(baseformaps, numberOfSpace >=1)

Afternoon <- filter(baseformaps4, DayPeriod == 'Afternoon')

We observe that occupancy rates vary by different time periods of the day. In the morning, occupany is predominantly low, as shown by the darker colors. In the afternoon, occupany is high all throughout the street segments on record. This makes sense as the area of study is mostly in downtown Seattle, where we would expect a lot of activity to occur. The occupancy rate drops in the evening time - we interpret this as most people leave the downtown area back to their homes. At night, occupancy drops even further, possibly reflective of most people being home and not in stores and offices.

4. OLS Regression Model

4.1 Kitchen Sink Model

We used occupancy ratio as our dependent variable, thus, we have built a linear model. We started it as a Kitchen Sink model - including every variable from out main data, which we believed to significantly influence our dependent variable.

#Set Up
options(scipen = 999)
epsg <- 4326 #set projection for all spatial data

We partitioned our final dataset into train and test subsets, where 75% of the data is train and 25% of the data is test. We use the train dataset to train our model and later apply the final model into the test data, where we will predict our average Occupancy rate on unseen data.

finalData<-parkingStNoZero
set.seed(336)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(finalData$avgOcc, p=.75, list = FALSE, times = 1)
train <- finalData[ trainIndex,]
test  <- finalData[-trainIndex,]

We run the Kitchen Sink model, which includes all the initial predictors in the dataset.

#Kitchen Sink Model
set.seed(125)

regParkingOccupancy <- lm(avgOcc ~ Side + DayPeriod + AreaFull + vehCounts + numberOfSpace +
                                   RateCost + ARTDESCRIP + SPEEDLIMIT + ONEWAY + SEGLENGTH + 
                                   SURFACEWID + NATIONHWYS + STREETTYPE + SLOPE_PCT +
                                   CLASS_DESC + maxBldgType + bldgTypeCat +
                                   wtScore, data = train)
summary(regParkingOccupancy)

The plot below shows how our predictions compare to the actual observed values from the train set. A perfectly accurate model would show that the points lie along the red line. However, the best fit line (shown in blue) shows that our predictions were not as accurate. It shows that our predictions were mostly below the observed data. One reason could be that most of the observations are on places with intensive commercial and institutional activities, and we do not compute the height of the buildings in each area. For example, a tall office and commercial building in the downtown area generates significant demand for parking, but that is rated in our model the same way we rate a gas station/convenience store in a mixes zone, because we lack more information about the characteristics of the building.

4.2 Model Validation

To evaluate the accuracy of our model, we used cross validation of 50 folds using out train data.

#100 folds for cross validation
fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 50)
set.seed(825)

lmFit <- train(avgOcc ~ DayPeriod + 
                 AreaFull + 
                 vehCounts + 
                 numberOfSpace +
                 RateCost +
                 ARTDESCRIP +
                 SEGLENGTH + 
                 STREETTYPE +
                 CLASS_DESC +
                 maxBldgType +
                 wtScore,
               data = train, method = "lm", trControl = fitControl)

The final R2 was .61, and the mean absolute error (MAE) was .51 in a Scale of 0 to 24 (average occupancy ratio). Our mean absolute percentual errors was 4.5%. Had we tested our model without removing the unofficial parking stalls (numberOfParking = 0), our model R2 would be 0.003 and the RMSE 15430.

Even though our final model R2 decreased slightly (compared to 0.6104 from the Kitchen Sink Model) and our RMSE increased slightly (compared to 0.8411 from the Kitchen Sink), we prefer this model because we removed insignificant predictors and avoid overfitting the model.

It is hard to say that our model is generalizable because it was mostly trained on and tested on observations that mostly come from the downtown area of the city. Hence, if this model were to be applied in another region outside of Seattle, it is highly likely that the predictions be off. Hence, this model is more accurate to the street segments of Downtown Seattle.

Testing the Predictive Power of Our Model in Unseen Data

After fitting our final model, we tested the predictive power of our model in unseen data - the test data. We predicted for the average parking occupancy rates in Seattle.

#predict for test
regPred <- predict(reg1, test) 
regPredValues <- 
  data.frame(observedOccupancy = test$avgOcc,
             predictedOccupancy = regPred)
regPredValues <-
  regPredValues %>%
  mutate(error = predictedOccupancy - observedOccupancy) %>%
  mutate(absError = abs(predictedOccupancy - observedOccupancy)) %>%
  mutate(percentAbsError = abs(predictedOccupancy - observedOccupancy) / observedOccupancy)

Testing for a Change in Neighborhood Characteristic

To investigate if our model would be useful in an app the way we described in the beginning of this document, we made a copy of our testset and changed the neighborhood characteristic. We changed every residential (single family and multifamily) street segment to neighborhood/commercial zoning (to emulate the way our app would work for planners).

We began by making a copy of the test data and a copy of the CLASS_DESC column (called CLASS_COPY), which describes the type of zone representing each street segment. This is the column where we change the zoning type - for the purposes of demonstration, we use the example of changing Multi-Family and Single Family zones into Neighborhood/Commercial zones.

Using the table() command, we check to make sure we are correctly changing the factors. For example, we have 544 Multi-Family, 38 Single Family, and 1565 Neighborhood/Commercial observations. After changing the former two factors (544+38) we should result in a total of 2147 Neighborhood/Commercial observations (from 544+38+1565).

#create copy of test with changed CLASS_DESC (change of zoning)
# Multi-Family and Single Family to Neighborhood/Commercial
test2<-test
table(test2$CLASS_DESC)
## 
##                 Downtown       Major Institutions Manufacturing/Industrial 
##                     2425                      390                      168 
## Master Planned Community             Multi-Family  Neighborhood/Commercial 
##                        2                      544                     1565 
##   Residential/Commercial            Single Family 
##                     1219                       38
 #Multi-Family (544) and Single Family (38)
 #Neighborhood/Commercial (1565)
test2$CLASS_COPY<-test2$CLASS_DESC
test2$CLASS_COPY[test2$CLASS_COPY=='Multi-Family']<-'Neighborhood/Commercial'
test2$CLASS_COPY[test2$CLASS_COPY=='Single Family']<-'Neighborhood/Commercial'

#check correct change (Neighborhood/Commercial - 2147)
sum(test2$CLASS_COPY=='Neighborhood/Commercial') #2147
## [1] 2147

We replace the old CLASS_DESC column with the new CLASS_COPY columns to reflect a similar dataframe structure as the previous one.

#replace column
test3<-subset(test2[c(1:16,22,18:21)])

Because the column name was changed (CLASS_DESC to CLASS_COPY), we cannot call the same regression model as it will not idenfity the correct column name. To work around this, we created a copy of our model and only the changed variable column name so we can call test the data on a same model.

train2<-train
colnames(train2)[17]<-'CLASS_COPY'
reg1_copy <- lm(avgOcc ~ DayPeriod + 
             AreaFull + 
             vehCounts + 
             numberOfSpace +
             RateCost +
             ARTDESCRIP +
             SEGLENGTH + 
             STREETTYPE +
             CLASS_COPY + #column with changed neighborhood characteristics
             maxBldgType +
             wtScore,
           data = train2)

We now repeat the same process, predicting for the average occupancy rate for test set with zonal change (Multi-Family and Single Family to Neighborhood/Commercial).

#now predict for changed zone
regPredNew<-predict(reg1_copy,test3)
regPredNewValues<-
  data.frame(oldClass<-test$CLASS_DESC,
             newClass<-test3$CLASS_COPY,
             observedOccupancy = test$avgOcc,
             predictedOccupancy = regPred,
             newPredictions = regPredNew)

regPredNewValues<-
  regPredNewValues%>%
  mutate(error = predictedOccupancy - observedOccupancy) %>%
  mutate(absError = abs(predictedOccupancy - observedOccupancy)) %>%
  mutate(percentAbsError = abs(predictedOccupancy - observedOccupancy) / observedOccupancy) 
mean(regPredValues$absError)
## [1] 0.5205989

We cannot compare the newly predicted values against observed, as we do not have the observed values for the changed classes. Instead, here we built a dataframe with old and new zoning classes (other zones kept the same), the observed occupancy ratio, the predicted occupancy in the regular testset, and the prediction with the changed zoning.

As previously explained in our feature engineering process, commercial were weighted higher than residential areas, justified by the idea that commercial places are attraction points, meaning that greater activity and movement of people (parking and leaving) increases the overall average of parking occupancy. This means that we would expect our new predictions to be higher.

To verify this, we created a changed_obs column to compare the newPredicitons with the previous predictions (before a neighborhood change was made).

change_obs <- subset(regPredNewValues, oldClass....test.CLASS_DESC == "Single Family" |
                       oldClass....test.CLASS_DESC == "Multi-Family")
sum(change_obs$error)
## [1] 3.672207
change_obs$change_error <- change_obs$newPredictions - change_obs$predictedOccupancy
change_obs$moreorless <- ifelse(change_obs$change_error>0, 1,0)

change_positive <- subset(change_obs, moreorless==1)
change_negative <- subset(change_obs, moreorless==0)

sum(change_positive$change_error)
## [1] 0
sum(change_negative$change_error)
## [1] -79.9979
mean(change_negative$change_error)
## [1] -0.1374534

Despite not having observed values for the changed classes, we were surprised to verify that the new predictions had a lower occupancy ratio than the values on the normal testset. This lower prediction could also be due to chaning the CLASS_DESC column (from the Seattle Zoning Classifications) and not the weight score column (which was created from the Building Permits data). This indicates that our model needs further work in the way it interprets zoning as a variable.

5. Discussion

Our analysis provides occupancy ratios per street segment. When we started to look at the data and how to approach the spatial scale, we have imagined many ways to summarize the parking data. Census blocks looked as an adequate geographical unit to aggregate occupancy ratios, because we assumed people are willing to do short walks if that helps them finding a parking spot. However, we realized that street segments provide unique insight to the model, because at this scale we can account for features like street direction or type of street (major / collector / local street).

Having a prediction of occupancy ratio correlated to many different aspects of the built environment allow us to understand how those variables modify our model and, therefore, to build afterwards an application in which different settings of a parcel, of block, or area, could be adjusted according to future developments or zoning changes. That is how our model would contribute to the kind of tool we are suggesting for planners.

6. Limitations and next steps for improvement

Based on the results and analyses of our model, we can summarize some problems with the data wrangling that prevented us from building a better and stronger predictive model:

  • The data information is inconsistent, which prevented us to add variables that would increase our predictive power, such as whether the observation was in a week day or weekend, or in which season the observation occurred.

  • Weather data would probably be a good feature to include in the model, since people tend to drive, rather than walk or bike, in rainy or cold days. Unfortunately, this data is behind a paywall.

  • For analyzing the build environment, we have worked with building permits, and the zoning code. We understand that urban density plays a major role in creating more demand for parking spaces. We have searched for data about verticality of the buildings, but unfortunately, we havent found such data.

A.3 Combining parking data and parking rates for each year:

#2015
pk15_2<-
  pk15%>%
  group_by(Unitdesc,Side,DayPeriod,Area3)%>%
  summarize(vehCounts=sum(Total_Vehicle_Count),
            numberOfSpace = mean(Parking_Spaces),
            avgOcc=mean(AvgOccupancy))

colnames(pk15_2)[4]<-"AreaFull"
rates15<-subset(parkingrates15[c(3:7)])

parkRate15<-left_join(x=pk15_2,y=rates15,by="AreaFull",all.x=TRUE)
#add parking rate column and set to 9999
parkRate15$RateCost<-99999
parkRate15$RateCost<-ifelse(parkRate15$DayPeriod=='Morning',parkRate15$Morning,
                            ifelse(parkRate15$DayPeriod=='Afternoon',parkRate15$Afternoon,
                                   ifelse(parkRate15$DayPeriod=='Evening',parkRate15$Evening,
                                          ifelse(parkRate15$DayPeriod=='Night',parkRate15$Night,
                                                 parkRate15$RateCost))))
parkRate15$vehCounts<-ifelse(is.na(parkRate15$vehCounts),0,parkRate15$vehCounts)
parkRate15$numberOfSpace<-ifelse(is.na(parkRate15$numberOfSpace),0,parkRate15$numberOfSpace)
parkRate15$numberOfSpace<-ifelse(parkRate15$numberOfSpace==0,0.0001,parkRate15$numberOfSpace)
parkRate15$avgOcc<-ifelse(is.na(parkRate15$avgOcc),parkRate15$vehCounts/parkRate15$numberOfSpace,parkRate15$numberOfSpace)

any(is.na(parkRate15))
## [1] FALSE
